'''Cairo''' ({{IPAc-en|icon|ˈ|k|aɪ|r|oʊ}} {{respell|KY|roh}}; {{lang-ar|القاهرة}} {{Transl|ar|''al-Qāhira''}}; {{lang-fr|Le Caire}}, literally &quot;The Vanquisher&quot; or &quot;The Conqueror&quot;) is the capital of [[Egypt]], the largest city in [[Africa]] and the [[List of metropolitan areas by population|16th most populated metropolitan area]] in the world.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.prlog.org/10332580-cairo-alqahira-is-egypts-capital-and-the-largest-city-in-the-middle-east-and-africa.html |title=Cairo - &quot;Al-Qahira&quot;- is Egypt's capital and the largest city in the Middle East and Africa.|ref=harv|postscript=&lt;!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to &quot;.&quot; for the cite to end in a &quot;.&quot;, as necessary. --&gt;{{inconsistent citations}}}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;R.L. Forstall, R.P. Greene, and J.B. Pick, [http://www.uic.edu/cuppa/cityfutures/papers/webpapers/cityfuturespapers/session3_4/3_4whicharethe.pdf &quot;Which are the largest? Why published populations for major world urban areas vary so greatly&quot;], City Futures Conference, (University of Illinois at Chicago, July 2004) – Table 5 (p.34)&lt;/ref&gt; 

Cairo is also ranked as one of the most densely populated cities in the world.&lt;ref name=&quot;forbes1&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/2006/12/20/worlds-most-congested-cities-biz-energy-cx_rm_1221congested_slide.html|title=World's Densest Cities|date=21 December 2006|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=6 March 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Nicknamed &quot;The City of a Thousand [[Minaret]]s&quot; for its preponderance of [[Islamic architecture]], Cairo has long been a centre of the region's political and cultural life. Cairo was founded by the [[Fatimid Caliphate|Fatimid dynasty]] in the 10th Century, but the land composing the present-day city was the site of national capitals whose remnants remain visible in parts of [[Old Cairo]]. Cairo is also associated with [[Ancient Egypt]] due to its proximity to the ancient cities of [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]], [[Giza]] and [[Fustat]] which are nearby to the [[Great Sphinx of Giza|Great Sphinx]] and the [[Giza Necropolis|pyramids of Giza]].

The English and French names for the city (&quot;Cairo&quot;, and &quot;Le Caire&quot; respectively) are [[Corruption (linguistics)|corruptions]] of its [[Arabic]] name &quot;Al-Qahira&quot;. Egyptians today often informally refer to Cairo as ''Maṣr'' ({{lang-ar|مصر}}), the vernacular Egyptian pronunciation of ''Misr'', the name for Egypt itself, emphasizing the city's continued central importance in the country.&lt;ref&gt;{{Harvnb|Behrens-Abouseif|1992|p=8}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Harvnb|Golia|2004|p=152}}&lt;/ref&gt; Cairo has the oldest and largest film and music industries in the Arab World, as well as the world's second-oldest institution of higher learning, [[al-Azhar University]]. Many international media, businesses, and organizations have regional headquarters in the city, and the [[Arab League]] has had its headquarters in Cairo for most of its existence.

With a population of 6,758,581&lt;ref name=&quot;Capmas2006&quot;&gt;{{Cite document|url=http://www.msrintranet.capmas.gov.eg/ows-img2/xls/rep1ne.xls |publisher=Central Agency for Public Mobilisation and Statistics |title=Population and Housing Census 2006, Governorate level, Population distribution by sex |format=xls |accessdate=9 July 2009|ref=harv|postscript=&lt;!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to &quot;.&quot; for the cite to end in a &quot;.&quot;, as necessary. --&gt;{{inconsistent citations}}}}. Adjusted census result, as Helwan governorate was created on 17 April 2008 from a.o. parts of the Cairo governorate.&lt;/ref&gt; spread over {{convert|453|km2|mi2|lk=out}}, Cairo is by far the largest city in Egypt. With an additional ten million inhabitants just outside the city, Cairo resides at the centre of the [[List of metropolitan areas in Africa by population|largest metropolitan area in Africa]] and the [[List of urban areas by population|eleventh-largest urban area in the world]].&lt;ref name=&quot;demographia&quot;&gt;{{Cite document|url=http://www.demographia.com/db-worldua.pdf |title=Demographia World Urban Areas &amp; Population Projections |publisher=Demographia |month=April |year=2009 |accessdate=9 July 2009|ref=harv|postscript=&lt;!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to &quot;.&quot; for the cite to end in a &quot;.&quot;, as necessary. --&gt;{{inconsistent citations}}}}&lt;/ref&gt; Cairo, like many other [[Megacity|mega-cities]], suffers from high levels of pollution and traffic, but its [[Cairo Metro|metro]] – currently one of only two on the African continent – also ranks among the 15 busiest in the world,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url=http://en.apa.az/news.php?id=104441 |title=World metro systems by annual passenger rides |last=Mustafayev |first=Nicat |date=29 June 2009 |accessdate=9 July 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; with over 700 million passenger rides annually. The economy of Cairo was ranked first in the [[Middle East]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.citymayors.com/statistics/richest-cities-2005.html|title=The 150 Richest Cities in the World by GDP in 2005|accessdate=2010-11-11}}&lt;/ref&gt; and 43rd globally by ''[[Foreign Policy]]'''s 2010 [[global city|Global Cities Index]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.foreignpolicy.com/node/373401|title=The 2010 Global Cities Index}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==History==
{{See also|History of Egypt}}

===Initial settlements===
[[File:Fostat-329.jpg|right|thumb|upright|A rendition of [[Fustat]] from A.S. Rappoport's ''History of Egypt''|alt=A man on a donkey walks past a palm tree, with a mosque and market behind him.]]
The area around present-day Cairo, especially [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]], had long been a focal point of [[Ancient Egypt]] due to its strategic location just upstream from the [[Nile Delta]]. However, the origins of the modern city are generally traced back to a series of settlements in the first millennium. Around the turn of the 4th century,&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Hawass|Brock|2003|p=456}}&lt;/ref&gt; as Memphis was continuing to decline in importance,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite encyclopedia |year=2009 |title=Memphis (Egypt) |encyclopedia=Encarta |publisher=Microsoft |url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761573551/memphis_(egypt).html |accessdate=24 July 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5kwQXIiNw|archivedate=2009-10-31|deadurl=yes |ref=harv}}&lt;/ref&gt; the [[Roman Empire|Romans]] established a fortress town along the east bank of the [[Nile]]. This fortress, known as [[Babylon Fortress|Babylon]], remains the oldest structure in the city. It is also situated at the nucleus of Egypt's [[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Christian]] community, which separated from the Roman and Byzantine church in the late 4th century. Many of Cairo's oldest Coptic churches, including [[The Hanging Church]], are located along the fortress walls in a section of the city known as [[Coptic Cairo]].

After the [[Muslim conquest of Egypt]] in 641, [[Rashidun Caliphate|Rashidun]] commander [['Amr ibn al-'As]] established [[Fustat]] just north of Cairo and Babylon. At Caliph [[Umar|Umar's]] request, the Egyptian capital was moved from [[Alexandria]] to the new city.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Butler|2008|p=341}}&lt;/ref&gt; Fustat also became a regional centre of [[Islam]] and home to the [[Mosque of Amr ibn al-As]], the first [[mosque]] in Egypt.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Butler|2008|p=342}}&lt;/ref&gt; When the [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasids]] usurped the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyads]] in 750, they moved the capital to [[al-Askar]], which they had built just north of Fustat. In 868, under the [[Tulunids]], Egypt's capital was moved further north to their own settlement, [[al-Qatta'i]].&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Raymond|2000|pp=23–9}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, neither al-Askar nor al-Qatta'i achieved the prominence of Fustat; al-Askar had become indistinguishable from Fustat by the end of the 9th century, and al-Qatta'i was destroyed by the Abbasids when they recaptured Egypt in 905. With the Abbasids' second conquest, Fustat once again became the capital of Egypt. According to [[Encyclopædia Americana]], the city was founded by the second caliph, [[Omar ibn al-Khattāb]].&lt;ref name=Umar&gt;[http://www.agepedia.org/wiki/OMAR_I The American Encyclopedia of 1851]&lt;/ref&gt;

===Foundation and expansion===
{{See|History of Arab Egypt}}
{{See also|Saladin in Egypt}}

[[File:Muizz Street 2.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Muizz Street]], stretching from the [[Bab al-Fotouh|Northern Gates]] of Cairo to the [[Bab Zuweila|Southern Gates]] of the Newly Created city, was the city's first paved street, and the largest street as well.]]

In 969, led by General [[Gawhar al-Siqilli]], the [[Fatimid Caliphate]] conquered [[Egypt]] from [[Tunisia]] and established a new fortified city northeast of [[Fustat]]. It took four years for Jawhar to build the city, initially known as al-Manṣūriyyah,&lt;ref name=&quot;glsm96&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Glassé|Smith|2003|p=96}}&lt;/ref&gt; which later took its Modern name, Al-Qahira (Cairo) which was to serve as the new capital of the caliphate. During that time, Jawhar also commissioned the construction of [[al-Azhar Mosque]], which developed into the third-oldest university in the world. Cairo would eventually became a centre of learning, with the library of Cairo containing hundreds of thousands of books.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Meri|Bacharach|2006|p=451}}&lt;/ref&gt; When Caliph [[Al-Muizz Lideenillah|al-Mu'izz li Din Allah]] finally arrived from the old Fatimid capital of [[Mahdia]] in [[Tunisia]] in 973, the city was given its present name, ''al-Qahira'' (&quot;The Victorious&quot;), in reference to the caliph.&lt;ref name=&quot;glsm96&quot; /&gt;

[[File:Cairo-citadel-1800s.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Cairo Citadel]], seen above in the late 19th century, was built between 1176 and 1183|alt=A multi-domed mosque dominates the walled Citadel, with ruined tombs and a lone minaret in front.]]
For nearly two hundred years after Cairo was established, the administrative centre of Egypt remained in [[Fustat]]. However, in 1168, the Fatamids, under the leadership of [[Vizier]] [[Shawar]], set fire to Fustat to prevent Cairo's capture by the [[Crusades|Crusaders]].&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Daly|Petry|1998|p=213}}&lt;/ref&gt; Egypt's capital was permanently moved to Cairo, which eventually expanded to include the ruins of Fustat and the previous capitals of [[al-Askar]] and [[al-Qatta'i]]. While the Fustat fire successfully protected the city of Cairo, a continuing power struggle between Shawar, [[List of Kings of Jerusalem|King]] [[Amalric I of Jerusalem]], and [[Greater Syria|Syrian]] general [[Shirkuh]] led to the downfall of the Fatimid establishment.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Daly|Petry|1998|pp=213–5}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 1169, [[Saladin]] was appointed as the new vizier of Egypt and, two years later, he would seize power from the family of the last Fatimid caliph, [[Al-'Āḍid]].&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Daly|Petry|1998|p=215}}&lt;/ref&gt; As the first [[Sultan of Egypt]], Saladin established the [[Ayyubid dynasty]], based in Cairo , and aligned Egypt with the [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasids]], who were based in [[Baghdad]].&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Shillington|2005|p=438}}&lt;/ref&gt; During his reign, Saladin also constructed the [[Cairo Citadel|Citadel]], which served as the seat of Egyptian government until the mid-19th century.

In 1250, slave soldiers, known as the [[Mamluk]]s, seized Egypt and, like many of their predecessors, established Cairo as the capital of [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|their new dynasty]]. Continuing a practice started by the [[Ayyubid dynasty|Ayyubids]], much of the land occupied by former [[Fatimid Caliphate|Fatimid]] palaces was sold and replaced by newer buildings.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Raymond|2000|p=122}}&lt;/ref&gt; Construction projects initiated by the Mamluks pushed the city outward while also bringing new infrastructure to the centre of the city.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Raymond|2000|pp=120–8}}&lt;/ref&gt; Meanwhile, Cairo flourished as a centre of [[Islamic studies|Islamic scholarship]] and a crossroads on the [[spice trade]] route between Europe and Asia. By 1340, Cairo had a population of close to half a million, making it the largest city west of [[China]].&lt;ref name=&quot;sh199&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Shillington|2005|p=199}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Stagnation and Ottoman rule===
{{See|History of Ottoman Egypt}}
{{See also|Muhammad Ali's seizure of power}}
[[File:Ibrahim Pasha Statue (04).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]]'s Statue in the centre of the Opera Square in Cairo]]
Although it avoided [[Europe|Europe's]] stagnation during the [[Late Middle Ages]], Cairo could not escape the [[Black Death]], which struck the city more than fifty times between 1348 and 1517.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Shoshan|2002|p=4}}&lt;/ref&gt; During its initial, and most deadly, waves, approximately 200,000 people were killed by the plague,&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Bryne|2004|pp=104–5}}&lt;/ref&gt; and, by the 15th century, Cairo's population had been reduced to between 150,000 and 300,000.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Shoshan|2002|p=1}}&lt;/ref&gt; The city's status was further diminished after [[Vasco da Gama]] discovered a sea route around the [[Cape of Good Hope]], thereby allowing spice traders to avoid Cairo.&lt;ref name=&quot;sh199&quot; /&gt;

[[File:Cairo Panoramic View 03.png|thumb|left|Cairo during the sunset, minutes before the maghrib Prayer, from the Azhar park, with the Iconic Ottoman Mosque of Muhammed Ali in 2010]]

Cairo's political influence diminished significantly after the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottomans]] supplanted [[Mamluk]] power over [[Egypt]] in 1517. Ruling from [[Istanbul]], [[List of sultans of the Ottoman Empire|Sultan]] [[Selim I]] relegated Egypt to a mere [[province]], with Cairo as its capital.&lt;ref name=&quot;sh447&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Shillington|2005|p=447}}&lt;/ref&gt; For this reason, the history of Cairo during Ottoman times is often described as inconsequential, especially in comparison to other time periods.&lt;ref name=&quot;sh199&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://menic.utexas.edu/cairo/history/ottoman/ottoman.html |publisher=The University of Texas Center for Middle Eastern Studies |title=Ottoman Cairo |year=1995 |last=Rose |first=Christopher |coauthors=Linda Boxberger |work=Cairo: Living Past, Living Future |accessdate=30 July 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;wi225&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Winter|1992|p=225}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, during the 16th and 17th centuries, Cairo remained an important economic and cultural centre. Although no longer on the spice route, the city facilitated the transportation of [[Yemen]]i [[coffee]] and [[India]]n [[textile]]s, primarily to [[Anatolia]], [[North Africa]], and the [[Balkans]]. Cairene merchants were instrumental in bringing goods to the barren [[Hejaz]], especially during the annual [[hajj]] to [[Mecca]].&lt;ref name=&quot;wi225&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|İnalcık|Faroqhi|Quataert|McGowan|1997|pp=507–9}}&lt;/ref&gt; It was during this same period that [[al-Azhar University]] reached the predominance among Islamic schools that it continues to hold today;&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Winter|2004|p=115}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Daly|Petry|1998|pp=94–5}}&lt;/ref&gt; pilgrims on their way to hajj often attested to the superiority of the institution, which had become associated with Egypt's body of [[Ulema|Islamic scholars]].&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Winter|2004|pp=115–7}}&lt;/ref&gt; By the 16th century, Cairo also had [[Tower block|high-rise]] [[apartment|apartment building]]s where the two lower floors were for commercial and storage purposes and the multiple stories above them were [[renting|rented]] out to [[Leasehold estate|tenants]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|title=Traditional Islamic principles of built environment|first=Hisham|last=Mortada|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2003|isbn=0700717005|page=viii|ref=harv|postscript=&lt;!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to &quot;.&quot; for the cite to end in a &quot;.&quot;, as necessary. --&gt;{{inconsistent citations}}}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Under the Ottomans, Cairo expanded south and west from its nucleus around the [[Cairo Citadel|Citadel]].&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Winter|1992|p=226}}&lt;/ref&gt; The city was the second-largest in the empire, behind only Istanbul, and, although migration was not the primary source of Cairo's growth, twenty percent of its population at the end of the 18th century consisted of religious minorities and foreigners from around the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]].&lt;ref name=&quot;wi2267&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Winter|1992|pp=226–7}}&lt;/ref&gt; Still, when [[Napoleon I|Napoleon]] arrived in Cairo in 1798, the city's population was less than 300,000, forty percent lower than it was at the height of Mamluk—and Cairene—influence in the mid-14th century.&lt;ref name=&quot;sh199&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;wi2267&quot; /&gt;

The [[Campaign of Egypt|French occupation]] was short-lived as [[British Empire|British]] and Ottoman forces, including a sizable [[Albanians|Albanian]] contingent, recaptured the country in 1801.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sicker|2001|p=103}}&lt;/ref&gt; The British vacated Egypt two years later, leaving the Ottomans, the Albanians, and the long-weakened [[Mamluk]]s jostling for control of the country.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sicker|2001|p=104}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Afaf Lutfi Sayyid-Marsot|1984|p=39}}&lt;/ref&gt; Continued civil war allowed an Albanian named [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali Pasha]] to ascend to the role of [[commander]] and eventually, with the approval of the [[ulema|religious establishment]], viceroy of Egypt in 1805.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Sicker|2001|pp=104–5}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Modern era===
{{See|History of Egypt under the Muhammad Ali dynasty|History of modern Egypt}}
Until his death in 1848, [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali Pasha]] instituted a number of social and economic reforms that earned him the title of founder of modern Egypt.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Afaf Lutfi Sayyid-Marsot|1984|p=1}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|McGregor|2006|p=53}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, while Muhammad Ali initiated the construction of public buildings in the city,&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Shillington|2005|p=437}}&lt;/ref&gt; those reforms had minimal effect on Cairo's landscape.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Raymond|2000|pp=291, 302}}&lt;/ref&gt; Bigger changes came to Cairo under [[Isma'il Pasha]] (r. 1863–1879), who continued the modernization processes started by his grandfather. Drawing inspiration from [[Paris]], Isma'il environs a city of maidans and wide avenues; due to financial constraints, only some of them, in the area now composing [[Downtown Cairo]], came to fruition.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Raymond|2000|pp=313–4}}&lt;/ref&gt; Isma'il also sought to modernize the city, which was merging with neighboring settlements, by establishing a [[public works]] ministry, bringing [[natural gas|gas]] and lighting to the city, and opening a theater and opera house.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Raymond|2000|pp=311–3}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Abu-Lughod|1965|pp=436–44}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:Cairo Nile Towers.png|left|thumb|Today, high-rise buildings line the eastern edge of the Nile in central Cairo|alt=High-rises, including a multi-storey white building in the foreground, dominate a sunset view of Cairo alongside the Nile, which is shown flowing under a bridge carrying a busy street]]
[[File:Cairo - Garden City - Four Seasons Hotel from the Nile.JPG|right|thumb|Four Seasons Hotel in Cairo]]
The immense debt resulting from Isma'il's projects provided a pretext for increasing European control, which culminated with the [[1882 Anglo-Egyptian War|British invasion]] in 1882.&lt;ref name=&quot;sh199&quot; /&gt; The city's economic centre quickly moved west toward the [[Nile]], away from the historic [[Islamic Cairo]] section and toward the contemporary, European-style areas built by Isma'il.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Abu-Lughod|1965|pp=429–31, 455–7}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;hokhwi317&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Hourani|Khoury|Wilson|2004|p=317}}&lt;/ref&gt; Europeans accounted for five percent of Cairo's population at the end of the 19th century, by which point they held most top governmental positions.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Abu-Lughod|1965|p=431}}&lt;/ref&gt;
[[File:Grandhyatt haddara.jpg|right|thumb|[[Nile]] view of [[Grand Hyatt Cairo]] at night ]]
&lt;gallery&gt;
[[File:night.jpg]]||right|thumb| Cairo at night
&lt;/gallery&gt;

The British occupation was intended to be temporary, but it lasted well into the 20th century. Nationalists staged [[Egyptian Revolution of 1919|large-scale demonstrations]] in Cairo in 1919,&lt;ref name=&quot;sh199&quot; /&gt; five years after Egypt had been declared a British [[protectorate]].&lt;ref name=&quot;hokhwi317&quot;&gt;{{harvnb|Hourani|Khoury|Wilson|2004|p=12}}&lt;/ref&gt; Nevertheless, while this led to Egypt's [[Unilateral Declaration of Egyptian Independence|independence in 1922]], British troops remained in the country until 1956. During this time, urban Cairo, spurred by new bridges and transport links, continued to in expand to include the upscale neighborhoods of [[Garden City (Cairo)|Garden City]], [[Zamalek]], and [[Heliopolis (Cairo suburb)|Heliopolis]].&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Raymond|2000|pp=326–9}}&lt;/ref&gt; Between 1882 and 1937, the population of Cairo more than tripled – from 347,000 to 1.3 million&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Raymond|2000|p=319}}&lt;/ref&gt; – and its area increased from {{convert|1000|ha|km2 mi2|0|lk=in}} to {{convert|16300|ha|km2 mi2|0}}.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Raymond|2000|p=322}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The city was devastated during the 1952 [[Cairo Fire]], also known as Black Saturday, which saw the destruction of nearly 700 shops, movie theatres, casinos and hotels in Downtown Cairo.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite journal |url=http://www.ahram.org.eg/433/2011/02/04/457/55/Malafat.aspx |title=خسائر الحريق |date=12 May 2010 |journal=[[Al-Ahram]] |trans_title=The Fire Damage |language=Arabic |accessdate=2011-02-04 |ref=harv}}&lt;/ref&gt; The British departed Cairo following the [[Egyptian Revolution of 1952]], but the city's rapid growth showed no signs of abating. Seeking to accommodate the increasing population, [[President of Egypt|President]] [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]] redeveloped [[Midan Tahrir]] and the Nile [[Corniche]], and improved the city's network of bridges and highways.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Raymond|2000|p=349}}&lt;/ref&gt; Meanwhile, additional controls of the Nile fostered development within the island of [[Gezira Island|Gezira]] and along the city's waterfront. The metropolis began to encroach on the fertile [[Nile Delta]], prompting the government to build desert [[satellite town]]s and devise incentives for city-dwellers to move to them.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Raymond|2000|pp=343–5}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Despite these efforts, Cairo's population has doubled since the 1960s, reaching close to seven million (with an additional ten million in its [[urban area]]). Concurrently, Cairo has established itself as a political and economic hub for [[North Africa]] and the [[Arab world|Arab World]], with many multinational businesses and organizations, including the [[Arab League]], operating out of the city.

In 1992, Cairo was hit by a [[1992 Cairo earthquake|damaging earthquake]], that caused 545 deaths, 6512 injuries and left 50,000 people homeless.&lt;ref name=&quot;NGDC&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/nndc/struts/results?eq_0=5339&amp;t=101650&amp;s=13&amp;d=22,26,13,12&amp;nd=display|title=NGDC page on the Cairo earthquake|accessdate=9 June 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Satellite cities===
[[6th of October City]], west of Cairo, and [[New Cairo]], east of Cairo, are major urban developments which have been built to accommodate additional growth and development of the Cairo area.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/25/world/africa/25egypt.html &quot;To Catch Cairo Overflow, 2 Megacities Rise in Sand&quot;] article by Thanassis Cambanis in ''[[The New York Times]]'' August 24, 2010, accessed August 25, 2010&lt;/ref&gt; New development includes several high-end residential developments.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.sodic.com/our-developments/ Map of Greater Cairo &amp; SODIC Developments], accessed August 25, 2010&lt;/ref&gt;

==Geography==
[[File:View from Cairo Tower 31march2007.jpg|thumb|right|Cairo's focal point, the [[Nile]], adjacent to the European-inspired districts near the city's centre|alt=A sharp blue river divides the cityscape, which is primarily greenery and sparse low-rise buildings in the foreground, and dense with several modern high-rises in the background]]
Cairo is located in northern [[Egypt]], known as [[Lower Egypt]], {{convert|165|km|mi|-1}} south of the [[Mediterranean Sea]] and {{convert|120|km|mi}} west of the [[Gulf of Suez]] and [[Suez Canal]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=cairo+to+suez |work=WolframAlpha |publisher=Wolfram Research |accessdate=10 September 2009 |title=Cairo to Suez}}&lt;/ref&gt; The city is along the [[Nile|Nile River]], immediately south of the point where the river leaves its desert-bound valley and branches into the low-lying [[Nile Delta]] region. Although the Cairo metropolis extends away from the Nile in all directions, the city of Cairo resides only on the east bank of the river and two islands within it on a total area of {{convert|453|km2|mi2}}.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cairo.gov.eg/C17/C8/Cairo%20Maps/default.aspx|publisher=Cairo Governorate|accessdate=10 September 2009|title=Cairo Maps}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;citypop&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.citypopulation.de/Egypt.html |publisher=City Population |last=Brinkhoff |first=Thomas |accessdate=12 September 2009 |title=Egypt: Governorates &amp; Cities}}&lt;/ref&gt;
[[File:Cairo Nile River.jpg|thumb|right|The river [[Nile]] flows through Cairo, here contrasting ancient customs of daily life with the modern city of today.]]

Until the mid-19th century, when the river was tamed by dams, levees, and other controls, the Nile in the vicinity of Cairo was highly susceptible to changes in course and surface level. Over the years, the Nile gradually shifted westward, providing the site between the eastern edge of the river and the [[Mokattam]] highlands on which the city now stands. The land on which Cairo was established in 969 (present-day [[Islamic Cairo]]) was located underwater just over three hundred years earlier, when [[Fustat]] was first built.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Collins|2002|p=125}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Low periods of the Nile during the 11th century continued to add to the landscape of Cairo; a new island, known as ''Geziret al-Fil'', first appeared in 1174, but eventually became connected to the mainland. Today, the site of ''Geziret al-Fil'' is occupied by the [[Shubra]] district. The low periods created another island at the turn of the 14th century that now composes [[Zamalek]] and [[Gezira Island|Gezira]]. [[Land reclamation]] efforts by the [[Mamluk]]s and [[Ottoman Empire|Ottomans]] further contributed to expansion on the east bank of the river.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Collins|2002|p=126}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:Islamic-cairo-street.jpg|left|thumb|The streets of [[Islamic Cairo]], adorned by [[Islamic architecture]], are narrower and older than those in the city centre|alt=Several people walk down a small empty lane overshadowed on both sides by three-story buildings with shrouded balconies and windows of Islamic style]]
Because of the Nile's movement, the newer parts of the city – [[Garden City (Cairo)|Garden City]], [[Downtown Cairo]], and Zamalek – are located closest to the riverbank. The areas, which are home to most of Cairo's [[diplomatic mission|embassies]], are surrounded on the north, east, and south by the older parts of the city. [[Old Cairo]], located south of the centre, holds the remnants of [[Fustat]] and the heart of Egypt's [[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Christian]] community, [[Coptic Cairo]]. The [[Boulaq]] district, which lies in the northern part of the city, was born out of a major 16th-century port and is now a major industrial centrer. The [[Cairo Citadel|Citadel]] is located east of the city centre around [[Islamic Cairo]], which dates back to the [[Fatimid Caliphate|Fatimid]] era and the foundation of Cairo. While western Cairo is dominated by wide boulevards, open spaces, and [[modern architecture]] of European influence, the eastern half, having grown haphazardly over the centuries, is dominated by small lanes, crowded tenements, and [[Islamic architecture]].

Northern and extreme eastern parts of Cairo, which include [[satellite town]]s, are among the most recent additions to the city, as they developed in the late-20th and early-21st centuries to accommodate the city's rapid growth. The western bank of the Nile is commonly included within the urban area of Cairo, but it composes the city of [[Giza]] and the [[Giza Governorate]]. Giza has also undergone significant expansion over recent years, and today the city, although still a [[suburb]] of Cairo, has a population of 2.7 million.&lt;ref name=&quot;citypop&quot; /&gt; The Cairo Governorate is just north of the [[Helwan Governorate]], which was created in 2008 when some of Cairo's southern districts, including [[Maadi]] and [[New Cairo]], were split off and annexed into the new [[governorate]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2008/894/eg6.htm |publisher=al-Ahram Weekly |last=Leila |first=Reem |number=894 |date=24–30 April 2008 |accessdate=12 September 2009 |title=Redrawing the Map}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Climate===
{{wide image|Panocairo1.jpg|900px|A panorama of the Nile showing Cairo tower in the middle and two major bridges on the far right and left.}}
In Cairo, and along the Nile River Valley, the climate is a [[desert climate]] (''BWh'' according to the [[Köppen climate classification]] system&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://koeppen-geiger.vu-wien.ac.at/pics/kottek_et_al_2006.gif |title=World Map of Köppen-Geiger Climate Classification |publisher=Köppen-Geiger |date= |accessdate=2010-01-22}}&lt;/ref&gt;), but often with high humidity due to the river valley's effects. Wind storms can be frequent, bringing [[Mineral dust|Saharan dust]] into the city during the months of March and April. High temperatures in winter range from {{convert|13|°C|0|abbr=on}} to {{convert|19|°C|0|abbr=on}}, while night-time lows drop to below {{convert|8|°C|0|abbr=on}}, often to {{convert|5|°C|0|abbr=on}}. In summer, the highs rarely surpass {{convert|40|°C|0|abbr=on}}, and lows drop to about {{convert|20|°C|0|abbr=on}}. Rainfall is sparse, but sudden showers do cause harsh flooding. In [[New Cairo]], a place of higher elevation than down town Cairo, the temperatures often drop below zero during winter causing morning frost. {{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}
{{-}}
{{Cairo weatherbox}}

==Infrastructure==
[[File:Cairo SPOT 1006.jpg|thumb|Cairo seen from [[SPOT (satellite)|Spot Satellite]]]]

===Health===
{{See also|List of hospitals in Egypt}}
Cairo, as well as neighbouring Giza, has been established as Egypt's main centre for medical treatment, and despite some exceptions, has the most advanced level of [[Health care|medical care]] in the country. Cairo's hospitals include the [[Joint Commission|JCI]]-accredited As-Salam International Hospital - Corniche El Nile; Maadi (Egypt's largest [[private hospital]] with 350 beds), [[Ain Shams University]] Hospital, Dar El Fouad Hospital, as well as [[Kasr El Aini Hospital|Qasr El Ainy General Hospital]].

===Education===
Cairo has long been the hub of education and educational services for Egypt and the region.
Today, Cairo is the centre for many government offices governing the [[Education in Egypt|Egyptian educational system]], has the largest number of educational schools, and [[Egyptian universities|higher learning institutes]] among other cities and governorates of Egypt.

