===Transportation===
{{Main|Transportation in Cairo}}
[[File:Metro-1-l.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Cairo Metro]]]]
[[File:Cairo Airport, Terminal 1.jpg|thumb|Terminal 1 in [[Cairo International Airport]]]]
[[File:12672-big-1-1290846656.jpeg|thumb|Cairo Taxi]]
[[File:Cairo Transport Authority.JPG|thumb|left|Cairo Transport Authority]]
[[File:Ramsesst.jpg|thumb|Ramses Street, one of Cairo's main arteries]]Transportation in Cairo comprises an extensive road network, [[rail system]], [[Rapid transit|subway system]], and maritime services. Road transport is facilitated by personal vehicles, taxi cabs, privately owned public buses, and [[Microbus#Van conversions|Cairo microbuses]]. Cairo, specifically Ramses Square, is the centre of almost the entire Egyptian [[transport network|transportation network]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}}

The subway system, officially called &quot;Metro (مترو)&quot;, is a fast and efficient way of getting around Cairo. It can get very crowded during [[rush hour]]. Two train cars (the fourth and fifth ones) are reserved for women only, although women may ride in any car they want.

An extensive road network connects Cairo with other Egyptian cities and villages. There is a new [[Ring road|Ring Road]] that surrounds the outskirts of the city, with exits that reach outer Cairo districts. There are flyovers and bridges, such as the Sixth of October bridge that, when the traffic is not heavy, allow fast {{Citation needed|date=November 2008}} [[Mode of transport|means of transportation]] from one side of the city to the other.

Cairo traffic is known to be overwhelming and overcrowded.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2006/779/feature.htm |title=Al-Ahram Weekly &amp;#124; Features &amp;#124; Reaching an impasse |publisher=Weekly.ahram.org.eg |date=2006-02-01 |accessdate=2009-05-05}}&lt;/ref&gt; Traffic moves at a relatively fluid pace. Drivers tend to be aggressive, but are more courteous at intersections, taking turns going, with police aiding in [[Road traffic control|traffic control]] of some congested areas.{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}}

On 25 October 2009 a passenger train ran into another one near [[Giza]], just outside Cairo.&lt;ref name=&quot;smh&quot;&gt;{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/world/egypt-train-crash-death-toll-rises-20091025-heeg.html |title=Egypt train crash death toll rises |publisher=smh.com.au |accessdate=2009-10-25 | date=2009-10-25}}&lt;/ref&gt; Local news agencies reported at least 25 people dead.&lt;ref name=&quot;9and10News&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.9and10news.com/category/story/?id=179211 |title=9&amp;10 News: The nuclear issue...National emergency...Deadly train crash |publisher=www.9and10news.com |accessdate=2009-10-25 }}&lt;/ref&gt; A local resident, Samhi Saleh Abdel Al, told reporters that ''&quot;the first train stopped after hitting a [[Water Buffalo|cow]] and 10 minutes later the second train arrived at full speed.&quot;''&lt;ref name=&quot;Al Jazeera&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2009/10/20091024181043439993.html |title=[[Al Jazeera]] English - Middle East - Deadly train crash in Egypt |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] [http://english.aljazeera.net/english.aljazeera.net] |accessdate=2009-10-25 }}&lt;/ref&gt; One of the two trains was travelling from Cairo to [[Assiut]], while the other was said to have been en-route to [[Faiyum|Fayoum]] from Giza.&lt;ref name=&quot;Maan News&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.maannews.net/eng/ViewDetails.aspx?ID=234685 |title=Maan News Agency: Fourteen killed as trains collide south of Cairo |publisher=www.maannews.net |accessdate=2009-10-25 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Around 55 people were injured.&lt;ref name=&quot;SkyNews&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/World-News/Two-Trains-Crash-Outside-Cairo-Egypt-Killing-At-Least-25---Police/Article/200910415415965?lpos=World_News_Top_Stories_Header_1&amp;lid=ARTICLE_15415965_Two_Trains_Crash_Outside_Cairo%2C_Egypt%2C_Killing_At_Least_25_-_Police |title=Two Trains Crash Outside Cairo, Egypt, Killing At Least 25 – Police |work= Sky News |accessdate=2009-10-25 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

